\section{Plant communities and pollinators decline}
Angiosperms, the so called flowering plants, emerged around 135 Mya, according to fossil evidence, but molecular clock studies suggest an earlier origin, possibly around 150 million years ago or even before \parencite{vanderkooiOriginsFloweringPlants2020}. Since then, they have undergone rapid and extensive expansion, now encompassing around 90\% of all land plant species. They now provide the most abundant portion of biomass on this planet. In the terrestrial environment, their interactions with other living organisms are dominant factors in community structure and function; they underpin all nutrient and energy cycles \parencite{butelFloweringPlantReproduction2024a}. They reproduce through structures that produce and disperse male gametophytes (pollen), and another that receives the incoming pollen on the stigma. There, the compatible pollen grain is hydrated and can initiate the formation of a tube that penetrates and grows inside the pistil until it reaches the ovule allowing the transport of the male genetic material (\Cref{fig:pollinationinangiosperm}, \cite{willmerPollinationFloralEcology2011}) . 

