They are usually hermaphrodite, the same individual counts with both female and male structures \parencite{rennerRelativeAbsoluteFrequencies2014}. Several potential advantages of these dual sex functions have been proposed, including reproductive assurance, efficient pollinator attraction, and the ability to optimize resource allocation to maximize reproductive success over the flowering season. This strategy increases the number of offspring produced and nearly doubles mate diversity in flowering plants populations  \parencite{christopherHermaphroditismPromotesMate2019a}. Flowering plants are sessile and cannot directly control pollen dispersal and pollen receipt. There are many strategies for the transfer of the pollen from an anther to a conspecific stigma. It can be done trough an abiotic agent which can be wind, water, or  gravity, but the majority of them use animal pollinators to achieve reproduction \parencite{willmerPollinationFloralEcology2011}. The efficiency of the process depends on the mean percentage of pollen removed from flowers (removal efficiency) and on the mean percentage of removed pollen reaching stigmas. This is highly variable between taxa and depends on the fisiological and morphological characteristics of the pollen and on the transport agent \parencite{johnsonEconomyPollenDispersal2023}. The active pollination, driven by animals, is found to be more efficient when compared to closely related passively pollinated plant species \parencite{pellmyrActivePollinationDrives2020}.\\

Pollination networks are the most species-rich of all mutualistic networks, globally involving 88\%  of all angiosperm species, at least 1 million insect species belonging to several orders among other animals, with high taxonomic diversity, birds, mammals and reptiles  \parencite{ollertonHowManyFlowering2011}. The complexity and diversity of these interactions are now at risk. There is increasing evidence that many European pollinating species are declining. For instance, the last IUCN European Red List indicates that in Europe, 37\% of all hoverfly species \parencite{vujicPollinatorsEdgeOur2022}, 15\% of butterflies \parencite{vanswaayEuropeanRedList2025}, and 10\% of wild bees \parencite{nietoEuropeanRedList2014} are threatened with extinction and all these percentages have been increasing in the last decade. Even domesticated pollinators, such as managed honeybees, show significant declines in North America and Europe \parencite{aizenGlobalStockDomesticated2009}.   

Pollinator loss leads to plant loss, and vice versa \parencite{bondMutualismsMatterAssessing1997a}; pollinating animals may not directly affect most other key ecosystem processes, but they can exert important indirect effects in plant community diversity and range; so that the persistence of effective pollination can be a good measure of ecosystem health \parencite{lundbergMobileLinkOrganisms2003}. Since pollination involves specific interactions, any habitat effect that alters the distribution or abundance of a particular species pose potential risks to the associated partners creating coextintion patterns \parencite{vieiraPlantpollinatorCoextinctionsLoss2013a}. \\

Anthropic activity can lead to a series of changes in the habitat that can have immediate and noticeable consequences but can also cause an extinction debt that only becomes apparent years or decades later. Meaning that plant species that lose their pollinators may persist in the habitat with asexual reproduction, but are in an evolutionary sense at a dead end \parencite{kolbHabitatFragmentationReduces2008}. 

Other than damaging ecosystems' health and resilience the pollinators decline is also a risk for our own economic system and food security. Pollinators (bees, insects, other animals) are critical for a wide range of nutritious crops, almost 75\% of cultivated plant species  rely on insects for fruit and seed production  \parencite{kleinImportancePollinatorsChanging2006}. When their role fails arises a lack of nutrients that usually translates to economical and social instability. The report by \textcite{schoonoverSocietalSecurityImplications2022} highlights that some countries are particularly vulnerable because they rely heavily on crops that require animal pollination and are often forced in a monocolture system, for example Ivory Coast, New Zealand, Samoa and New Caledonia, exacerbating inequality to resource access. The 28–61\% of global crop systems are pollinator limited.  Realistic increases in pollinator visitation could mitigate crop yield shortfalls attributable to pollinators decline \parencite{turoInsufficientPollinatorVisitation2024}. However, existing studies cannot adequately distinguish between natural fluctuations in pollinator populations and human-induced damaging changes. Lately major initiatives are being set up to record and conserve native bees, and more in general pollinating fauna but this of course occurs mainly in Europe and North America. Major gaps remain in our knowledge regarding the status and trends of pollinating insects \parencite{willmerPollinationFloralEcology2011}. \\



