\section{Main threats to pollinators and pollination}

\paragraph{Habitat fragmentation}
Human activities such as urbanization, industrial agricultural practices, extractivism and deforestation are causing habitat fragmentation, spatial isolation of similar communities. In general, plant and pollinator diversity and population size decrease with the decreasing size and habitat connectivity. Smaller, isolated populations face higher risks of inbreeding depression and genetic drift, reducing genetic diversity and increasing the risk of extintion \parencite{willmerPollinationFloralEcology2011}. A global meta‑analysis by \textcite{miguel-penalozaHabitatFragmentationDegradation2023} demonstrates that habitat fragmentation and degradation influence fine‑scale spatial genetic structure in plants. In plant communities they also can shift plant phenological patterns, contract flowering periods and increase the risk of local pollinator extirpation. Pollination dynamics are altered thanks to changes in pollinator behaviors and  plant densities. Habitat fragmentation often leads to the extirpation of specialist species and results in an influx of generalists. The reason is that habitat fragmentation also changes the composition of the flora and scatters floral resources, so any remaining pollinator may need to behave as generalists in order to survive. Still, the current knowledge of the potential ecological consequences of habitat fragmentation is limited, especially regarding their effects on a long-term scale and at landscape scales \parencite{xiaoDiverseEffectsHabitat2016}. 

\paragraph{Intensive agriculture}
Practices of intensive agriculture are among the most important causes of the loss of biodiversity. Driven by the need to maximize crop yields and meet global food demands, intensive agriculture has profound negative impacts on the environment and ecosystems. These practices often involve excessive use of chemical fertilizers, pesticides, monocropping, and large-scale irrigation systems. Such activities degrade soil quality, reduce biodiversity, and contribute to water pollution through runoff laden with agrochemicals \parencite{apoorvaNegativeImpactsIntensive2024}. All kind of hedgerows, margins, or patches of uncultivated land, typical in traditional agriculture, are erased leading to the  degradation of native pollination services, by reducing nesting possibilities and disrupting mutualistic plant–pollinator interactions \parencite{hirayamaImpactsAgriculturalIntensification2025}. The use of agrochemicals can have a direct negative effect on pollinators lives (especially where spraying time coincides with flowering time), or it can eliminate key host plants for all pollinators \parencite{osumanuGlobalBiodiversityDecline2023}. Some biocides surely contribute to this phenomenon, like the use of pest control, in particular those used on a large scale against mosquitoes. Further confirmation can be found in the multiple studies that have found the presence of residues of phytosanitary products  both in the body of bees and in hive matrices, such as honey, pollen and wax \parencite{HttpsWwwlife4pollinatorseuIt}. 
Grazing has been for long part of many ecosystems processes, playing a role in maintaining plant diversity, increasing light availability, opening ground for nesting and increasing soils’ nutrient levels. However, overgrazing, takes out too large amounts of plant tissues, removing flowers and potential flowers with strong impact on the pollinator community composition  \parencite{apoorvaNegativeImpactsIntensive2024}.

All these consequences of intensive agriculture are made evident by the innumerable phenomena of mortality and depopulation of honey bee families and other wild pollinating fauna that have been reported in the last decades \parencite{pereiraImpactsAgricultureIntensification2025}. 


\paragraph{Fires}
Fire has a central role in pollination and plant sexual reproduction in fire-prone ecosystems like the Mediterranean. The increase in absolute production of fruits and seeds that follows a fire in such ecosystems, suggests that it benefits plant reproduction. The reason is usually an increased abiotic resources pool, nutrients are more easily available. However, increased fire frequency due to anthropogenic changes can alter the nature of the response to fire altering communities composition and leading to pollination network disruption \parencite{carboneFireEffectsPollination2025}. 


\paragraph{Alien species}
As stated in \textcite{kovacs-hostyanszkiThreatsBenefitsInvasive2022} alien plant species are also an important threat to pollination systems and communities.
They generally threaten native flora and usually advantage hoverflies and honey bees over wild bees, reducing overall community diversity.
When plant alien species is integrated into an existing native plant–pollinator networks, this translates into changes in the whole network structure. This generally leads to pollinators depending more on alien plants than on native species. Consequently, even though native plants have long co-evolved with native pollinators, alien species often become more central, frequently causing significant losses in native floral resources throughout the year \parencite{vilaInvasivePlantIntegration2009,kovacs-hostyanszkiThreatsBenefitsInvasive2022}. Another effect of invasive plant species is increased competition for pollinator insects among entomophilous plants, which also negatively affects native species \parencite{dupontImpactIntroducedHoney2004}.

About alien fauna, the introduction of mammals such as livestock, but even rats, cats, rabbits (direct consequence of modern human activities), can be very problematic for biodiversity. They alter the balance between herbivore insects and their predators and allow the spreading of diseases.
The introduction of invasive insects can lead to the ecological success of few generalists taking over the native specialists, altering overall competition \parencite{kisvargaSystematicReviewNative2025}.
\textit{Apis} is probably the most ubiquitous introduction worldwide: it does influence diversity and abundance of other flower visitors, but the result of the impact remains unclear \parencite{goulsonEffectsIntroducedBees2003}.  
