\paragraph{Climate change}
Finally, climate change, it strongly affects mutualistic interactions between plants and its pollinators. The phenology of diverse organisms has changed in response to ongoing global warming. It leads to a shorter overlap in the timing of flowering and pollinator foraging, potentially resulting in the weakening or loss of specific plant–pollinator interactions and reducing the fitness of both partners and leading to reproductive loss. This is likely to make entomophilous plants more vulnerable to climate change impacts than anemophilous species \parencite{fisogniComplexitiesPhenologicalShifts2025}.

Phenological asynchrony in pollination is already well documented. The analysis of \textcite{menzelEuropeanPhenologicalResponse2006} undoubtedly demonstrated that species' phenology is responsive to temperature changes in Europe, recording a mean advance of spring/summer by 2.5  $\frac{^\circ\text{C}}{\text{day}}$, and a delay of leaf colouring and fall by 1.0 $\frac{^\circ\text{C}}{\text{day}}$.
Another study based on 19 years of monitoring and a snow removal experiment in a cool-temperate forest in northern Japan indicates that phenological mismatch tends to occur when snow melts early but subsequent soil warming progresses slowly. Thus, modification of the snowmelt regime could be a major driver disturbing spring phenology in northern ecosystems \parencite{kudoWhenSpringEphemerals2019}.

Plant ranges are also shifting towards higher latitudes, but still not as fast as moving animals’ ranges are. At a socio-economic level, spatial mismatches between plants and their main pollinators have been found even for crops, a reproductive loss, and so a decrease in production, in food plants exists because of a tinier co-occurrence overlap of flowers and pollinating insects \parencite{oliveiraClimateChangeWill2025}. 

Spatial or temporal variation in the abiotic characteristics of the context affects flower abundances and plant community composition, this of course has consequences on pollinator visitation, pollination network structure, pollen transfer dynamics, and seed production. In addition changes in the availability of flowers, fruits, and seeds are likely to impact on all other trophic levels \parencite{trunschkeEffectsClimateChange2024}.

\section{Mediterranean habitat}
The Mediterranean basin  (\Cref{fig:Location of the Mediterranean Basin Hotspot}) is recognised as a biodiversity hotspot, its flora diversity is outstanding with 15,000 to 25,000 species, 60\% of which are unique to the region. About one third of the Mediterranean fauna is also endemic \parencite{cuttelodMediterraneanBiodiversityHotspot2008}.

