The area is included in one large ecoregion defined by one major habitat type "Mediterranean shrublands and woodlands" according to \textcite{olsonGlobal200Priority2002}. This habitat type occurs close to coastlines in between 35° and 45° latitude, in areas where human influence has been long standing. There are five Mediterranean zones and they have similar characteristics, but there are important differences within each of the regions.

In particular in the mediterranean basin, the area is now subject to substantial anthropogenic stress from increasing fires, overgrazing, tree removal for fuel use, and the demands of human agriculture and urbanization. It is the hotspot that has the lowest percentage of natural vegetation remaining of any hotspot. Urbanization, coastal development, pollution, and unsustainable exploitation of natural 
resources are just some of the many human activities that are leading to an ever-increasing number of 
Mediterranean species to be facing a high 
risk of extinction. \parencite{cuttelodMediterraneanBiodiversityHotspot2008}.

The abiotic conditions here are characterized by strong seasonality, with mild wet winters and hot dry summers; the climate is very predictable during the different year phases so that plant growth development and reproduction follow a very precise pattern \parencite{medailBiodiversityHotspotsMediterranean1999}. 
  

\subsection{Vegetation patterns}
The Mediterranean Basin is mainly covered by scrub, sparse grass, or bare rock. However, there are scattered evergreen trees that suggest the earlier presence of mixed forests \parencite{spanoMediterraneanPhenology2024}. Mediterranean soils are often shallow, stony, and moderately acidic, limiting water retention and nutrient availability. Studies in Spain and Italy show that these soil conditions favor grasses, perennials, shrubs, and bulbous plants, with scattered small spiny trees \parencite{garcia-carmonaRecoveryMediterraneanSoils2023}. Many plants since soil is often nutrient and water poor have developed mutualistic relationships with nitrogen-fixing bacteria and deep, extensive root systems . So in the Mediterranean vegetation there is an important number of adaptations to drought, grazing, and frequent fire regimes \parencite{sardansPlantsoilInteractionsMediterranean2013}. These disturbances maintain diversity high by preventing the final stages of succession. However, lately native grazers have usually been replaced by abundant livestock and wildfires have higher frequency and intensity having the opposite effect \parencite{ruffaultIncreasedLikelihoodHeatinduced2020}.
Compared to temperate habitats Mediterranean sites present high percentages of dioecy. Most plants are entomophilous but there is a high proportion of wind-pollinated plants too. Plant diversity is very high, but plant phenology variation is rather limited, most are generalists and monophilic plants are below 10\% \parencite{willmerPollinationFloralEcology2011}.  


\subsection{Pollinators patterns}
The Mediterranean Basin is one of the richest regions globally for wild bees. Recent biodiversity surveys highlight the extraordinary diversity of bee species in the area, confirming high endemism rates and species richness \parencite{schneiderBeesMediterraneanBasin2024}. The basin has been called "A land for flowers and bees" by \textcite{petanidouLandFlowersBees2005}, emphasizing the importance of bee-pollinated Mediterranean shrubs and the high diversity of solitary bees compared to social bees. In this communities in fact wild bees dominate interactions, while honeybees (social bees) are less central than in other ecosystems \parencite{herreraGradualReplacementWild2020}.

The composition of the flower-visiting fauna may fluctuate enormously between seasons and years, depending on both biotic and abiotic factors \parencite{sgolastraTemporalActivityPatterns2016}. But considering the number and identity of insect taxa, and the number of plant species in bloom, the highest diversity is found in spring \parencite{herreraPollinationRelationshipsSouthern1988}.

