\section{Gello Revival project and study aim}

This research has been performed in the initial phase of the "Gello Revival" project, which was designed to establish a baseline to describe the pollination ecology traits of the area of interest. To do so, this baseline focuses specifically on assessing the current state of flowering plant communities and flower-visiting insects, thereby evaluating biodiversity and health of the local pollination networks.
The collection of this preliminary, ex-ante monitoring data is fundamental as it creates a scientific reference framework that will inform the criteria for forthcoming ecological restoration actions. Such interventions may include the targeted implementation of specific plant species to reinforce pollinator communities or the creation of natural infrastructure to enhance insect reproduction and habitat quality.
Subsequent monitoring phases will directly utilize this baseline to evaluate the effectiveness of these implemented restoration measures.

The project focuses on agricultural landscapes as they are recognized as among the ecosystems most degraded by human activity and are now a central priority for European Union conservation policy. Even if such modified ecosystems are not intrinsically rich in biodiversity, improving their 
health, resilience and biodiversity will render them more self sustaining and resilient to catastrophic events, such as floods, droughts, fires and disease. This study directly aligns with the objectives of the 2024 EU Nature Restoration Law wich aims to restore a broad range of degraded ecosystems, habitats and species across the EU’s land and seas. This landmark regulation mandates Member States to develop National Restoration Plans (NRPs) aimed at returning degraded terrestrial, marine, urban, forest, and agricultural habitats to good ecological condition. NRPs must be founded on comprehensive territorial monitoring and the identification of tailored measures for different habitat types. Within the Specific Restoration Targets within the Nature Restoration Regulation \parencite{EUNatureRestorationLaw2026}, we find pollination network and agricultural ecosystems restoration, to improve pollinator diversity and reverse the decline of pollinator populations, and to enhance biodiversity in agricultural ecosystems. So, the data generated by this project extends its relevance beyond the immediate local context where it was implemented. It also serves as a valuable case study that can contribute to shaping broader restoration norms, assessing the effectiveness of applied practices, and, ultimately, informing and guiding habitat-specific management strategies in line with emerging EU policy frameworks. 
\\

Within the project area, the analysis specifically targets former cover crops and natural zones sorrounding them, comprehending distinct vegetation types such as Mediterranean Maquis, herbaceous Meadows, and Riparian corridors. By examining these different habitats, the study aims to characterize their differences in ecological structures and functions. 

In this research using the data collected within the project we analyze:

\begin{itemize}
	\item  Flowering plant communities' diversity across 3 different habitat types and across months (April to October)
	
	\item Pollination Networks' diversity across 3 different habitat types and across months (April to October)
\end{itemize}



